{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"[PASS 1 — G6 Approach soundness, mechanism & alternative-selection] Independent review; all correctness reasoning grounded in the live reducer/differ/compaction code.\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (criteria this chunk passes):\n- G6 FITNESS-FOR-PURPOSE (solves the NAMED problem, not a proxy): the \"Why\" precisely diagnoses why the raw-history \"ever-seen\" projection (the `local_label_intent` pattern) fails CLOSED across compaction, and the fix targets exactly that. Verified: `process_snapshot` (src/rebar/reducer/_processors.py:515-519) blindly copies EVERY `compiled_state` key onto state, so a `managed_refs` key folded by the reducer and serialized by `compact.py` (compiled_state built via `reduce_ticket`, src/rebar/_commands/compact.py:92,103,129) \"survives compact_ticket for free\" is mechanically TRUE.\n- G6 APPROACH SELECTION: I generated two structurally-different alternatives — (a) recompute the ever-seen union on demand by scanning raw event history (the `local_label_intent` shape consumed at outbound_differ.py:1365-1372), and (b) a sidecar provenance store OUTSIDE `compiled_state`. (a) is the very approach the plan rejects with a grounded compaction-survival argument (compact.py folds/strips originals, so a pre-snapshot removal is lost on re-derive). (b) is strictly worse on codebase-alignment + blast-radius (forfeits the existing process_snapshot/compaction/byte-parity machinery, adds reducer I/O). Chosen approach is defensibly at-least-as-good on every axis — PASS; alternatives discarded (not written into the plan).\n- G6 MECHANISM (concurrency/atomicity): the fold + migration-seed run inside the deterministic single-threaded reducer replay, so the \"seed when absent\" check-then-seed is NOT a TOCTOU. Strict reducer-side monotonicity (never pruned by UNLINK — `process_unlink` at :243-246 only shrinks `deps`) keeps the resurrection window closed; deferring reclamation to a reconcile-time prune event avoids the prune-vs-fold hazard. Sound.\n- G6 MECHANISM (empty/back-out): gate defaults missing `managed_refs` -> empty -> returns False (additive-only: no remove/clobber/churn), doubling as a safe no-op back-out. Well-specified fail-safe.\n- G6 POSITIVE RATIONALE: PRESENT and strong (compaction-survival, single provider-agnostic primitive, fail-safe default, explicit back-out). No rationale finding.\n\nFINDINGS (three load-bearing mechanism under-specifications; all independently re-verified against code — they corroborate the prior G6 comment of 1782537415419929001 and add the migration-ordering item):\n\n- [ ] Specify HOW the gate's CONSUMER normalizes a PEER (Jira) ref to the direction-distinguished local logical `(kind, target)` before the `managed_refs` lookup. The Jira \"Blocks\" type collapses BOTH `blocks` and `depends_on` onto one link type, disambiguated only by side: inbound_differ.py:492-502 maps a Blocks link's inward side to `depends_on` and outward side to `blocks`. `managed_refs` keys on direction-distinguished kinds {parent,blocks,depends_on,relates_to}, so a direction-collapsed peer link has no unique key without an explicit normalization rule. The plan rightly puts the gate on \"local logical refs\" but never states the consumer must first resolve the collapsed peer link to the correct kind/direction — so a locally-managed `depends_on` could be looked up as `blocks` and the gate would wrongly deny (resurrect) or wrongly approve a removal. (The link-child wake-inn-parse flagged this as a within-child gap; it belongs to the PARENT gate contract.)\n  criteria: [G6]\n  location: plan \"What\" / gate definition (\"operates on local logical refs\"); AC1 (\"normalized (kind, target)\"); inbound_differ.py:492-502\n  evidence: \"inbound maps Blocks inward->depends_on, outward->blocks (line 502) — one Jira type yields two direction-distinguished local kinds\"; \"managed_refs keys on (kind,target) — a direction-collapsed peer link is non-unique without a normalization rule the plan omits\"\n  suggested_fix: State in the gate contract that the consumer passes an ALREADY-normalized local logical ref (kind+direction resolved via the same inward/outward rule as inbound_differ), and add a gate unit test covering a Blocks link whose inward vs outward side maps to depends_on vs blocks, asserting the correct membership decision for each.\n\n- [ ] Specify that the parent-EDIT fold captures the DISPLACED prior parent. There is no dedicated parent processor — parent changes flow through the generic last-writer-wins `process_edit` (src/rebar/reducer/_processors.py:319-338), which REPLACES `state[field_name]` (line 338) and never sees the prior value post-merge. A monotonic union of \"every parent ever managed\" therefore requires reading `state[\"parent_id\"]` BEFORE the merge and folding BOTH old and new parents; folding only the post-merge value silently drops the prior parent and re-opens the resurrection window for RE-PARENTED tickets. AC1 asserts the monotonic property but does not name this ordering dependency. (Also note `process_edit`'s `if field_name not in state: continue` guard at line 328 means `managed_refs` cannot be folded by the generic EDIT path — it needs an explicit fold hook.)\n  criteria: [G6]\n  location: AC1 (\"folded from CREATE/LINK/parent-EDIT ... never reduced by UNLINK/detach\"); src/rebar/reducer/_processors.py:319-338 (process_edit), :56 (process_create parent_id)\n  evidence: \"process_edit is LWW with no dedicated parent processor — the displaced parent_id is unrecoverable once `state[field_name] = new_value` runs (line 338)\"; \"plan folds 'from parent-EDIT' but does not specify pre-merge capture of the prior parent, which is load-bearing for the stated strictly-monotonic union\"\n  suggested_fix: In the parent-EDIT fold, read the current state[\"parent_id\"] (old parent) BEFORE applying the merge and fold BOTH old and new (kind=parent) targets; add a unit test that re-parents A->B and asserts managed_refs contains both (parent,A) and (parent,B), and that a later detach of B still propagates.\n\n- [ ] Specify WHERE in the reduce path `managed_refs` seeding runs and that it executes as a post-replay finalization step (after the SNAPSHOT restore AND after all post-snapshot CREATE/LINK/parent-EDIT folds), NOT inside `process_snapshot`. `process_snapshot` (_processors.py:515-519) blindly copies compiled_state keys and would NOT seed an absent key; a pre-feature SNAPSHOT simply lacks `managed_refs`. If seeding ran at restore-time BEFORE a same-pass UNLINK, the seed-then-unlink ordering could mis-record. The plan says seeding happens \"on the FIRST reduce/restore where managed_refs is absent\" but leaves the insertion point and its ordering relative to UNLINK/fold unspecified — the exact ordering AC2's \"later unlink propagates\" depends on.\n  criteria: [G6]\n  location: plan \"Migration\" section + AC2 (\"When managed_refs is absent ... the reducer seeds it from current deps + parent_id; a test proves ... its later unlink propagates\")\n  evidence: process_snapshot (_processors.py:515-519) is a blind key-copy with no seed branch; the seeded value must derive from the FULLY-reduced deps + parent_id, which are only materialized post-replay (state[\"updated_at\"] finalization runs at :656-658); the plan leaves the hook location and ordering vs same-pass UNLINK unstated.\n  suggested_fix: State that seeding is a finalization pass over the fully-reduced state (current deps + parent_id) run after replay completes and after the monotonic folds, so a seeded pre-feature ticket's later UNLINK operates on an already-populated set; have the AC2 test compact under OLD code (no managed_refs key), then seed+unlink and assert propagation."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782538322461260001,"uuid":"9af7221e-484e-409d-b8ba-0cd3dfbea35a"}